--- body ---
eaks when a ticket's acceptance criteria are already met
in the codebase — either because the work was done as a side effect of
another ticket, or because the ticket described a condition that never
existed (e.g., 0039: `git fsck --unreachable` was already absent).

When the invariant breaks, pick-ticket keeps selecting the ticket on every
beat. Each false pick burns ~$5 of orchestrator budget and a 30-minute slot.
Ticket 0039 was picked three nights in a row before being caught manually.

The fix must span three tiers because each has a different latency:

**Tier 1 — housekeeping** (every 12h, conditional): first line of defense.
Closes already-done tickets during the hygiene pass, before pick-ticket runs.
Cannot be the only gate: up to 12h stale, so pick-ticket may visit a
falsely-open ticket 2–3 times within the gap.

**Tier 2 — pick-ticket** (every beat): lightweight exit-criteria check during
candidate assessment. For `cache:miss` tickets (body changed) or tickets
where recent commits touched relevant files — a cheap grep is sufficient
for most exit criteria. Emit `CLOSED: <id>` (new signal) and loop back to
pick again. No orchestrator budget burned.

**Tier 3 — start-ticket** (per execution): last resort, already implemented
(2026-04-29). After reading the ticket and before creating any branch, verify
exit criteria. If met, call `/ticket-close <id> already-done` and stop.
Always load-bearing regardless of upper tiers.

### Cache interaction

The `erg` cache hashes only the ticket body. A `cache:hit` means the ticket
text is unchanged — it says nothing about whether the code it describes has
been implemented. Housekeeping and pick-ticket therefore need a second signal:
`git log --since=<last-check>` on files relevant to the ticket. Recent commits
on those files → re-verify exit criteria even for `cache:hit` tickets.

Housekeeping can use the same log-line cache pattern as sweep:
```
{ts} claude note housekeeping-check: exit-criteria-met hash:{bodyhash}
```
Body hash stable → skip re-check. Body or relevant files changed → re-check.

## Actions

1. **Housekeeping tier**: add an "open ticket audit" phase to the housekeeping
   skill. For each open ticket: if body `cache:miss` OR recent commits touch
   relevant files → grep/check exit criteria → close if met, write
   `housekeeping-check:` log line with body hash either way.

2. **Pick-ticket tier**: during candidate assessment, for `cache:miss` tickets
   and tickets with recent relevant commits, check trivially-verifiable exit
   criteria (grep-based). If met, call `/ticket-close <id> already-done`,
   write `sweep-skip` log line, and exclude from this run. Emit `CLOSED: <id>`
   to stdout so beat.py can loop.

3. **beat.py**: handle `CLOSED: <id>` lines from pick-ticket output — loop
   back and pick again rather than proceeding to orchestrator with a stale pick.

4. **Tier 3** (start-ticket): already in place as of 2026-04-29. No further
   action needed; it remains the safety net.

## Test

Simulate the 0039 scenario: create an open ticket whose exit criteria are
"string X does not appear in file F", ensure F does not contain X, run
pick-ticket → verify ticket is closed and `IDLE` or a different ticket is
returned rather than the pre-solved one.

## Exit criteria

- An open ticket whose exit criteria are already met is closed by housekeeping
  on the next run, without being picked by pick-ticket
- If housekeeping is stale (< 12h), pick-ticket closes the ticket and loops
  to pick a genuine candidate — no orchestrator invocation for a pre-solved ticket
- start-ticket remains as final safety net (no regression from 2026-04-29 fix)
- beat-log shows no `outcome: done` with `branch: null` on a ticket that was
  already done at pick time
